Huge thank you to the heroes that saved this beautiful turtle! Via @thedodo

Trapped in a net, turtles are dragged through the water with no access to the surface to breathe, causing them to drown. It's estimated that some 4,600 sea turtles are killed by fishing nets and hooks every year in U.S. waters.

node.text:
~
.
Via @johndownerproductions

Bottlenose dolphins are filmed apparently getting high on secretions from pufferfish. The pufferfish secrete a neurotoxin that in high doses can kill but in small doses seemingly have a narcotic effect.

Video: 'Dolphins - Spy in the Pod' narrated by David Tennant
.
.
.

Huge thank you to the rescuers in this video 💚 Unfortunately not all turtles are this lucky. Once trapped in a net, turtles are dragged through the water with no access to the surface to breathe, causing them to drown. It's estimated that some 4,600 sea turtles are killed by fishing nets and hooks every year in U.S. waters alone ☹️
Video via @thedodo

node.text:
.
Guys as you may already know the conditions in Australia have been getting worse. Our fellow Australian influencers have come together and created a way for you to donate to the right organisations.
.
They have selected 6 organizations that desperately need our help. @BrinkleyDavies is personally aware of dozens of wildlife and animal rescues, and CFS crews that are missing out on donations, and are on the frontlines.
We, as Australian influencers have come together to ask you to please help our people and our animals in anyway you can. Australia is crying out for your help!
.
Follow the link in our bio to show your support 😭 Thankyou from the bottom of our hearts for watching!
.
#AustraliaWeAreWithYou

@sharksneedlove , @tristanguttridge and @go_native_freediving are working on a short, to long term strategy which involves rescue, aid and boat donations to Bahamians.
.
There’s more detail on GoFundMe (link in @sharksneedlove’s bio). PLEASE donate if you can. Every single penny contributes towards fuel, water etc. and WILL make a difference.
Thanks to all those doing what they can to support the Bahamas in their time of need. 💙 
Huge thanks to @sharksneedlove for everything she is doing! 🙌🏽

node.text:
The most chilled diving session 💦  Would you go diving here?

Besides its beautiful, clear-water diving spot, Ginnie Springs, Florida is also known as the perfect destination for a camping and kayaking trip. The area was privately owned for a while, but since the 90’s, the park has been opened to the public – and it has been a favourite in Florida ever since. 

Insider tip: Ginnie Springs has three different diving sites, including the Devil’s Spring System (for experienced divers), the Ginnie Ballroom (for those just beginning their cave diving journey) and Santa Fe River.

📍Ginnie Springs, Florida

Video by @andrewdesloover ft. @bjgriffinmusic

node.text:
Video by @paulnicklen 🐻 “Alaska's McNeil River is a dangerous place for a mother brown bear and her cubs during the final salmon run of the year. Dozens of large males crowd the shores, each looking for their share of fish to ensure survival through the coming winter. When this young male got too close for one mother's liking, she made it clear his presence was unwelcome. Shot on assignment for @SeaLegacy with @AndyMaser and @Kyle.Roepke.”

node.text:
You ever get that feeling something is sneaking up behind you? 🦈
Video by @juansharks: “Trust that instinctual notion when ur diving around sharks.  It is so important to be aware and alert, like a predator 😉. This is “Kalihi” the tiger shark just casually approaching me from behind.  I actually was looking around and I saw Kalihi go under the boat but I  was focused on filming shark ID “Nikki” with @oceanramsey that I lost track of Kalihi for a quick minute and I felt like she knew that.  One of the most important guides to follow while diving with sharks is to look around and have predatory awareness.”

#respectful #sharkdiving #safetyfirst @oneoceandiving #oahu #tigersharks #changingperceptions #getpeopletocare #aboutsharks #weneedsharksalive #ApexPredatorNotMonster #sharks #shark #diving #freediving #scubadiving #marinelife #sealife #oceanljfe #animals #wildlife #nature #underwater

This beautiful sharks name is Zola, the name Zola is of African origin meaning “piece of earth.” Which is beautifully symbolic when we consider how sharks are such important pieces of earth.. It’s also neat, that two of our newest squad members are sailing the Caribbean on a boat named Zola❤️🦈
@sailingzola

node.text:
Actual footage and A Rare Sighting of a Glass Octopus Reveals its Nearly Transparent Membrane in Extraordinary Detail⁣
⁣
On a 34-day expedition around the Phoenix Islands Archipelago, marine scientists from the Schmidt Ocean Institute captured exceptionally rare footage of the elusive glass octopus. With a speckled, iridescent membrane, the aquatic animal is almost entirely transparent—only its optic nerve, eyes, and digestive tract are visible to humans—and sightings like these are so infrequent that scientists previously resorted to studying the species only after pulling it from the stomachs of its predators.⁣
⁣
Source: thisiscolossal.com⁣
Video by: @schmidtocean⁣
Via @earthpix

Dolphin drifting 🐬⁣ via @bbcearth
⁣
These dolphins are hunting in waters only a few centimetres deep, using a technique called hydroplaning. As fish move into shallower water, the dolphins usual hunting techniques no longer work. Instead they pump their tails to gain speed and hydroplane, allowing them to catch fish even in the shallowest waters. ⁣
⁣
Footage by © BBC NHU⁣ @bbcearth
